Title: Dracula
Credit: Screenplay adaptation of
Author: Bram Stoker's novel (1897, public domain)
Draft date: 7/18/2026

====

FADE IN:

EXT. CARPATHIAN MOUNTAIN ROAD - NIGHT

Wolves howl in the distance. A rickety calèche rattles along a narrow mountain pass. Inside, JONATHAN HARKER (20s, English solicitor, travel-worn) clutches his coat against the cold.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
I had for a long time back been developing the age-old idea that when one is going to a new place, one should not be too effusive, in setting out, in expressing what one expects to find there.

The DRIVER, face obscured beneath a wide hat, cracks a whip. Blue flames flicker eerily along the roadside -- the driver stops repeatedly to mark them with stones.

EXT. BORGO PASS - CONTINUOUS

The calèche halts at a crumbling stone bridge. A black carriage waits, drawn by coal-black horses.

DRIVER
(in heavily accented English)
You are early tonight, my friend.

The mysterious coachman only smiles thinly and gestures for Harker to transfer. Reluctant, Harker climbs aboard.

CUT TO:

EXT. CASTLE DRACULA - COURTYARD - NIGHT

A vast, crumbling castle looms against the stars. The carriage stops. When Harker turns to thank the driver, he is gone -- and a tall, pale figure in black stands at the entrance, an antique lamp in hand.

COUNT DRACULA
(courtly, faint accent)
Welcome to my house. Enter freely, and of your own will.

He does not move to shake hands.

JONATHAN HARKER
Count Dracula?

COUNT DRACULA
I am Dracula, and I bid you welcome, Mr. Harker, to my house.

Harker steps inside. The door swings shut behind him with a heavy, final sound.

INT. CASTLE DRACULA - GREAT HALL - CONTINUOUS

A long table set with a single meal. The Count does not eat.

COUNT DRACULA
I trust you will forgive me if I do not join you -- I have already dined, and I never eat.

Harker eats uneasily under the Count's unblinking gaze.

DISSOLVE TO:

INT. CASTLE DRACULA - HARKER'S ROOM - NIGHT (DAYS LATER)

Harker writes urgently in a journal by candlelight.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
I am a prisoner, and I know it. I have not seen the Count eat or drink. He never appears in daylight hours.

He crosses to a mirror to shave -- and realizes with a jolt that the Count, standing directly behind him, casts no reflection.

A hand grips Harker's shoulder. He spins, cutting himself. A drop of blood falls. The Count's eyes flash with sudden hunger, restrained only with visible effort.

COUNT DRACULA
(low, controlled)
Take care how you cut yourself. It is more dangerous than you think in this country.

He snatches away Harker's crucifix necklace and flings it aside.

CUT TO:

INT. CASTLE DRACULA - HARKER'S ROOM - NIGHT (LATER)

Moonlight floods the chamber. Three pale, beautiful WOMEN drift into the room, their eyes hungry, their beauty unsettling.

WOMAN IN WHITE
(caressing, hungry)
He is young and strong. There are kisses for us all.

Harker, paralyzed with dread and fascination, cannot move as she leans close --

The Count BURSTS in, seizing her by the throat, fury contorting his face.

COUNT DRACULA
(roaring)
How dare you touch him, when I had forbidden it? This man belongs to me!

He flings her back and turns to the others.

COUNT DRACULA (CONT'D)
Back, all of you! When I am done with him, you shall kiss him at your will.

He tosses them a small sack that moves and whimpers faintly. The women descend on it instead.

Harker faints.

FADE OUT.

FADE IN:

EXT. WHITBY HARBOR - NIGHT (WEEKS LATER)

A violent storm. A derelict Russian schooner, the DEMETER, runs aground on the rocks, sails in tatters. Townsfolk gather with lanterns.

TOWNSMAN
There's no one at the helm!

They board. Below deck, they find the ship's log and, lashed to the wheel, the CAPTAIN -- dead, a crucifix still clutched in his rigid hand.

A large black dog leaps from the wreck and vanishes into the darkness of the churchyard above the town.

CUT TO:

INT. MINA MURRAY'S ROOM - WHITBY - DAY

MINA MURRAY (20s, warm, intelligent) writes a letter, worried, having received no word from her fiancé Jonathan in weeks. Her friend LUCY WESTENRA (20s, vivacious, pale of late) enters, distracted.

MINA
You look tired, Lucy. You've been sleepwalking again.

LUCY WESTENRA
I dreamed of red eyes, Mina. And something at the window.

Mina notices two small marks on Lucy's throat, dismisses them as a pin-prick.

CUT TO:

INT. SEWARD'S ASYLUM - DR. SEWARD'S STUDY - NIGHT

DR. JOHN SEWARD dictates into a phonograph, troubled.

DR. SEWARD
(into phonograph)
Renfield's case grows stranger by the day. He begs for flies, then spiders, then birds -- each meant to consume the last, as though he means to accumulate life itself.

A knock. His old friend and mentor, PROFESSOR VAN HELSING, enters -- elderly, sharp-eyed, unshaken by strangeness.

PROFESSOR VAN HELSING
John, I have seen your patient. And I must now see Miss Lucy. Her illness is not of this world we like to think we understand.

CUT TO:

INT. LUCY'S BEDROOM - NIGHT (LATER)

Lucy lies pale and weak, garlic flowers strung around the window per Van Helsing's strict instruction. Van Helsing checks on her.

VAN HELSING
(to himself, grim)
Keep the flowers close about her throat. Whatever comes, do not remove them.

He exits to rest. Lucy's mother, unaware, enters and -- finding the smell unpleasant -- removes the garlic wreath and opens the window for air.

A grey mist creeps in in the moonlight.

CUT TO:

INT. LUCY'S BEDROOM - MORNING

Van Helsing and Seward burst in to find Lucy deathly pale, the wounds on her throat deeper, her mother dead of shock in a chair nearby.

VAN HELSING
(devastated, urgent)
We must give blood, now, or we lose her by morning.

A transfusion, performed with grim haste. Lucy's fiancé ARTHUR HOLMWOOD offers his own blood without hesitation.

CUT TO:

EXT. HIGHGATE CEMETERY - NIGHT (WEEKS LATER)

Rain falls on rows of tombs. Van Helsing, Seward, Holmwood, and QUINCEY MORRIS gather grimly outside a marble tomb marked WESTENRA.

VAN HELSING
(quiet, resolute)
What we do tonight, we do for love, and for God, though it will seem the cruelest thing any of us have done.

They open the tomb. It is empty.

Later, a pale figure in white drifts through the cemetery, a small child in her arms -- LUCY, transformed, her sweetness curdled into something hungry and cold.

LUCY (THE UNDEAD)
(sweetly, terribly)
Arthur! Come to me. Leave these others and come to me, my husband!

Arthur, horrified and heartbroken, is held back by Van Helsing as Lucy hisses and retreats, dropping the child unharmed.

CUT TO:

INT. WESTENRA TOMB - DAY (LATER)

By daylight, the men return. Van Helsing hands Arthur a wooden stake.

VAN HELSING
It is you who loved her best who must set her soul free. Do not falter.

Arthur, weeping, drives the stake home. Lucy's corpse convulses once and is still -- her face, in death, finally peaceful again.

ARTHUR HOLMWOOD
(broken, grateful)
Now she is really dead. It is like a holy task.

CUT TO:

INT. SEWARD'S ASYLUM - STUDY - NIGHT (LATER)

Jonathan Harker, recovered and married to Mina, joins the group along with Van Helsing, Seward, Holmwood, and Morris around a table covered in maps and papers.

JONATHAN HARKER
He has fifty boxes of earth from Transylvania, scattered across London. Each one a refuge.

VAN HELSING
Then we hunt him box by box, and we drive him from this city, until he has nowhere left to hide.

MINA HARKER
(quietly)
And if he comes for me?

VAN HELSING
(gently, resolved)
Then we will be ready.

CUT TO:

INT. MINA'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

The men, believing Mina safe and sedated, keep watch elsewhere in the house. A mist seeps beneath the door and coalesces into DRACULA, looming over the bed.

He forces Mina to drink from a wound at his own breast -- a horrific, binding communion.

COUNT DRACULA
(cold, triumphant)
You are now to me flesh of my flesh, blood of my blood.

The men burst in too late, brandishing a crucifix and a sacred wafer. Dracula recoils, hissing, and dissolves into mist, fleeing through the window.

MINA HARKER
(sobbing, marked)
Unclean! Unclean! I must touch him no more, kiss him no more -- I am unclean.

VAN HELSING
(firm, tender)
No. You are the bravest of us all, and we will end this, for your sake.

CUT TO:

EXT. TRANSYLVANIAN FOREST ROAD - DUSK (WEEKS LATER)

A frantic pursuit. Gypsies transport a large box on a cart toward Castle Dracula, racing the setting sun. Harker, Morris, and the others intercept on horseback as snow begins to fall.

QUINCEY MORRIS
(shouting, drawing a blade)
The sun is nearly down! We must open it now!

A brutal skirmish. Morris is wounded but presses on. Harker hacks through the lid of the crate to reveal Dracula within, weakening as the light fades.

Harker's blade slashes the Count's throat; in the same instant, Morris drives his bowie knife into Dracula's heart.

The Count's face, for one final instant, shows something like peace -- and then crumbles to dust before them.

QUINCEY MORRIS
(dying, smiling)
It was worth this to make her free.

Mina weeps over Morris as the scar upon her forehead -- there since Dracula touched her -- fades away in the winter light.

FADE OUT.

INT. HARKER HOME - DAY (YEARS LATER)

Jonathan and Mina, older now, sit with a young son -- named, in part, for Quincey Morris -- as Jonathan reads from an old bundle of journals and letters.

JONATHAN HARKER (V.O.)
We were struck with the fact that, in all the mass of material, there is hardly one authentic document -- nothing but a mass of typewriting. We could hardly ask anyone to accept this as proof of so wild a story. And yet -- we know it to be true.

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
